Attention: NEVER charging smartphone wirelessly
Practical, but harmful
Inductive technology via QQi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come onto the market that support wireless charging and sell very well - especially the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July. Although wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature adds battery battery
Researchers warn against the wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick, this is extremely harmful to the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat generation. If a mobile phone is charged normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. During wireless charging, however, the researchers have always measured over 30 degrees even even the perfect alignment of the smartphone on the charging path. If the mobile phone is a little next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wt age of the charging pad also increases, which in turn increases the power consumption.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature is a decisive factor for the durability of batteries. Every single degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery not only loses capacity, but it also does last last so long overall. Thus, the service life is lower. Therefore, the researchers advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since a battery replacement on modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently even increased the costs of a battery replacement - - for all iPhones.
Praktisch
The technology is extremely convenient: simply place the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are now even installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without annoying cable clutter and tedious plug-in cheting. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transmission) asseris a worldwide standard, in which exceptionally even Apple participates, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be used in exceptional cases.
