Comet crossed crossed by other star Solar system
Astronomers are currently observing a comet from the depths of space. This was only achieved before. The comet allows conclusions to be drawn about other solar systems.
What was initially only a guess is now confirmed: An interstellar guest crosses through our solar system. The comet from the depths of space was christened 2I / Borisov after its discoverer and has aroused the interest of astronomers around the world.
The well-travelled comet was discovered on August 30 by the amateur astronomer Gennady Borisov at the Margo Observatory in Crimea - with a self-made telescope of 65 centimetres in diameter. Follow-observations of various observatories not only confirmed that it is an unknown comet, but also showed that it did not come from our solar system.
After 1I /' Oumuamua in 2017, 2I / Borisov is only the second interstellar object to be seen during a flight of our solar system.
2I / Borisov offers astronomers the rare chance to gain close insights into a foreign solar system before it disappears forever again again Initial observations show that the interstellar comet is similar to those of our own system, as the astrophysical institute of the Canary aries reported. " The current speed of the comet is high, about 150,000 kilometers per hour, which at this distance is well above the typical speeds of objects orbiting the Sun, " reported Davide Farnocchia from the US space agency Nasa in a statement.
According to the analyses, the comet is on a so-called hyperboola orbit that leads it out of our system - and clearly of interstellar origin, as the International Astronomical Union (IAU) announced. It is also responsible for the naming and categorization of celestial bodies. In honor of its discoverer, the interstellar tail star, which was initially listed under the catalog number C / 2019 Q4, was given the designation 2I / Borisov, whereby the first part of the name indicating that it is the second interstellar object discovered in our solar system.
The astronomers are lucky: In contrast to 1I /' Oumuamua, 2I / Borisov has already been sighted in approach. This, the researchers have many months to investigate. " The object will reach its brightness in mid-December December and then be visible with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020, " explained Farnocchia. " Thereafter, it will only be observed with larger, professional telescopes until October 2020. "
